Hypocriſy is conſidered, by all Moraliſts, as the moſt deſpicable and infamous Diſeaſe of the Soul; it diſcovers a Senſe of the Grace and Beauty of a fair Character, but generally carries with it a total Abſence of all good Qualities. It aims at Eſteem, by artfully concealing the latent Imperfections, and exhibiting to the public Eye a gloſſy Appearance of ſomething amiable and honeſt. But unleſs the Mind is thoroughly weeded, in ſpight of every artful Diſguiſe, the lurking Miſchief will, one Time or other, break out, and as Perſeus expreſſes it, like a wild Fig-tree, force its Way through the very Liver;
— Quae ſemel intus
Ianata eſt, rupto jecore exierit Caprificus. Since I have mentioned this Satiriſt, it coincides with my preſent Scope, to obſerve, that there is not in any Author ancient or modern, a nobler Deſcription of a Man of real Honour, than what is found in two Lines of his Writing; I ſhall tranſcribe his Words, becauſe the Paſſage is highly beautiful, and for the Sake of the mere Engliſh Reader, I ſhall add Mr. Dryden's excellent Tranſlation.

A Reputation otherwiſe obtained muſt certainly afford very little Satisfaction, and it will ſtill adminiſter leſs, when we conſider, that it is only, as Shakeſpear calls it, 〈◊〉 HONOUR, gained from the ignorant, from the ſelf •••• reſted, the mean, and the contemptible,;
